{"cursor":"2493","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Nicholas' (Nikolaus) 'Mercator' (c. 1620, Holstein â 1687, Versailles), also\nknown by his Germanic name Kauffmann, was a 17th-century mathematician.\n\nHe lived in the Netherlands from 1642 to 1648. He lectured at the University of\nCopenhagen during 1648â1654 and lived in Paris from 1655 to 1657. He was\nmathematics tutor to Joscelyne Percy, son of the 10th Earl of Northumberland, at\nPetworth, Sussex (1657). He taught mathematics in London (1658â1682). In 1666 he\nbecame a member of the Royal Society. He designed a marine chronometer for\nCharles II, and designed and constructed the fountains at the Palace of\nVersailles (1682â1687).\n\nMathematically, he is most well known for his treatise Logarithmo-technica on\nlogarithms, published in 1668. In this treatise he described the Mercator\nseries, also independently discovered by Gregory Saint-Vincent:\n\n: \\ln(1 + x) = x - \\frac{1}{2}x^2 + \\frac{1}{3}x^3 - \\frac{1}{4}x^4 +\n:\\cdots.\n\nIt was also in this treatise that the first known use of the term [[natural\nlogarithm]] appears, in the Latin form log naturalis. His use of this term is\nsomewhat surprising, since it predates the development of infinitesimal\ncalculus, in which the most natural properties of this logarithm appear.\n\nTo the field of music he contributed the first precise account of 53 equal\ntemperament, which was of theoretical importance, but not widely practiced.\n","linknr":116,"url":"Nicolaus_Mercator","recorded":1371243651,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Nicholas_Mercator&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Nicholas_Mercator&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Nicholas_Mercator","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wi